  🔠 call_m8d5a79r | Return {'content': '## Summary\n\nA solid-state battery (SSB) is an electrical battery that uses a solid electrolyte to conduct ions between electrodes, instead of the liquid or gel electrolytes found in conventional batteries. It theoretically offers much higher energy density than typical lithium-ion batteries and can solve issues like flammability, but faces challenges in scalability and commercialization. (Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid-state_battery)\n\n## Key Points\n\n1.  **Core Definition & Advantage:** An SSB uses a solid electrolyte (e.g., ceramics, solid polymers) instead of liquid or gel, theoretically offering much higher energy density than conventional lithium-ion or lithium polymer batteries. (Source: [3], [4], [5])\n2.  **Key Technical Specifications:**\n    *   **Specific Energy:** Thin film type: 300–900 Wh/kg; Bulk type: 250–500 Wh/kg. (Source: Table data)\n    *   **Cycle Durability:** 10,000-100,000 cycles. (Source: [1])\n    *   **Nominal Cell Voltage:** Thin film type: 4.6 V; Bulk type: 2.5 V. (Source: Table data, [1], [2])\n    *   **Operating Temperature:** -50 °C to 125 °C. (Source: Table data)\n3.  **Potential Benefits:** Using metallic lithium for the anode and oxides/sulfides for the cathode enhances energy density. The solid electrolyte acts as an ideal separator, potentially solving problems of liquid electrolyte Li-ion batteries including flammability, limited voltage, unstable interface formation, poor cycling, and strength. (Source: [6])\n4.  **Current Use & Challenges:** SSBs are currently used in pacemakers, RFID, and wearable devices, offering enhanced safety and higher energy densities. Widespread adoption is challenged by energy/power density, durability, material costs, sensitivity, and stability. The market has yet to reach scalability and commercialization. (Source: [7], [8], "Developments in the late 20th..." paragraph)\n\n## Technical Details\n\n*   **Electrolyte Materials:** Proposed materials include ceramics (oxides, sulfides, phosphates) and solid polymers.\n*   **Electrode Materials:** Can use metallic lithium for the anode and oxides or sulfides for the cathode.\n*   **Self-discharge Rate:** 6% per month at 85 °C. (Source: [1])\n*   **Charge Temperature Interval:** -20 °C to 105 °C. (Source: Table data)\n\n## References & Citations\n\n- Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid-state_battery\n- [1] - Cycle durability, self-discharge, bulk type voltage\n- [2] - Thin film type voltage\n- [3] - Core definition (solid vs. liquid/gel electrolyte)\n- [4], [5] - Theoretical higher energy density vs. Li-ion\n- [6] - Benefits (solving flammability, etc.) and electrode materials\n- [7] - Current applications (pacemakers, wearables)\n- [8] - Challenges to adoption', 'links_on_page': ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Contents', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portal:Current_events', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:Random', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:About', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Contact_us', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Contents', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Introduction', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Community_portal', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:RecentChanges', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:File_upload_wizard', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:SpecialPages', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:Search', 'https://donate.wikimedia.org/?wmf_source=donate&wmf_medium=sidebar&wmf_campaign=en.wikipedia.org&uselang=en', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:CreateAccount&returnto=Solid-state+battery', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:UserLogin&returnto=Solid-state+battery', 'https://donate.wikimedia.org/?wmf_source=donate&wmf_medium=sidebar&wmf_campaign=en.wikipedia.org&uselang=en', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:CreateA