  🔠 call_x77zclhb | Return {'content': '## Summary\n\nThis article details recent advancements in solid-state battery (SSB) technology for electric vehicles, highlighting a shift from lab testing to real-world road trials by major automakers. Key developments include partnerships with specialized firms, breakthroughs in energy density and charging times, and projected timelines for mass production by the late 2020s.\n\n## Key Points\n\n1.  **Mercedes-Benz achieved the first road-going SSB prototype.** In collaboration with Factorial Energy, they integrated a lithium-metal SSB into a modified EQS, resulting in a 25% longer driving range (approx. 620 miles) compared to the standard model. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/, section: "From The Lab To The Real World")\n2.  **BMW is testing SSBs in an i7 mule.** Partnering with Solid Power, they are using a sulfide-based solid electrolyte to study cell expansion and temperature control. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/, section: "From The Lab To The Real World")\n3.  **Stellantis (with Factorial Energy) validated high-performance SSB specs.** Their batteries achieve an energy density of 375 Wh/kg and can charge from 15% to over 90% in approximately 18 minutes at room temperature. They also operate in a wide temperature range from -22°F to 113°F. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/, section: "Refining The Technology")\n4.  **Hyundai filed a patent for a cost-reducing SSB design.** The patent proposes a six-layer cell using a copper anode with a protective coating to prevent corrosion, aiming to simplify production. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/, section: "Refining The Technology")\n5.  **Toyota and Nissan target late-2020s for production SSBs.** Toyota aims for mass production by 2027, promising a 20% range increase and sub-10-minute charging. Nissan targets 2028 for its introduction. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/, section: "By The End Of The 2020s")\n\n## Technical Details\n\n*   **Core Technology:** Solid-state batteries replace the liquid or gel electrolyte in lithium-ion batteries with a solid electrolyte, which can be made from materials like glass, ceramic, or sulfide.\n*   **Promised Advantages:** The technology offers greater energy density, smaller form factors, better heat resistance, and faster charging compared to current lithium-ion batteries.\n*   **Stellantis/Factorial Specs:**\n    *   Energy Density: 375 Wh/kg.\n    *   Charging: 15% to >90% in ~18 minutes at room temperature.\n    *   Operating Temperature: -22°F to 113°F.\n*   **Hyundai Patent Design:** Envisions a six-layer cell: copper anode collector, protective coating, additional anode layer, solid electrolyte layer, cathode layer, and current collector layer.\n\n## References & Citations\n\n- Source Article: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/\n- Mercedes-Benz & Factorial Energy Collaboration (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/)\n- BMW & Solid Power Testing (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/)\n- Stellantis SSB Performance Specifications (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/)\n- Hyundai Solid-State Battery Patent (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/)\n- Toyota Mass Production Target (2027) (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/)\n- Nissan Introduction Target (2028) (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/)', 'links_on_page': ['https://carbuzz.com/', 'https://carbuzz.com/cars/', 'https://carbuzz.com/marketplace/', 'https://carbuzz.com/news/', 'https://carbuzz.com/features/', 'https://carbuzz.com/marketplace/', 'https://carbuzz.com/best-cars-of-the-year/', 'https://c